NBM2 TASK 2: LOGISTIC REGRESSION FOR PREDICTIVE MODELING¶

Student ID – 009412995 Student Name – Rishika Gottepally

Performance Assessment¶

Part I: Research Question¶

A.1 Which patients are at high risk of Re-admission and which are the features most significant to this re-admission rate?

A.2 The organization will benefit from knowing which variables need to be addressed and improved for a patient and it will help in decision making to reduce the re-admission rate.

Part II: Method Justification¶

B.1 The Response Variable is Binary (in our data set re-admission is Yes or No). /No Multicollinearity: None of the predictor variables are highly correlated with each other. /Independence: The observations are independent. /There is a Linear Relationship Between Explanatory Variables and the Logit of the Response Variable. /There are No Extreme Outliers.

B.2 IPython Jupyter notebook is used to perform the analysis.Python programming language has robust packages like pandas,numpy,matplotlib.pyplot,seaborn,scipy.stats,sklearn which would help in manuplating data with ease and scikit-learn provides a clean and consistent interface to tons of different models. It provides us with many options for each model, but also chooses sensible defaults.

B.3 Logistic regression is an appropriate technique to analyze the research question because our target variable "ReAdmis" is a binomial(yes or no). And we would like to identify the dependency of other indipendent variables ('Gender''Soft_drink','HighBlood','Stroke','Overweight','Arthritis','Diabetes','Hyperlipidemia',etc.) on re-admission rate of an individual patient.It will improve our understanding of increased probability of re-admission as we include or remove different independent variables & find out whether or not they have a positive or negative relationship to our target variable.

Part III: Data Preparation¶

C.1 My data goals will start with reading the csv file into python using read_csv from pandas,naming the imported dataset as md_df,checking for any missing data and following approriate imputation methods(mean,median or mode),renaming variable names for better understanding,encoding categorical variables having (yes/no) values to binary (either 1 or 0).Generating dummies for other categorical variables with more than 2 unique values.

C.2 The Original data set consits of [10000 rows x 52 columns].For the analysis certain customer related info and demographics colums are dropped 'CaseOrder', 'Customer_id', 'Interaction', 'UID', 'City', 'State','Income','County', 'Zip', 'Lat', 'Lng', 'Population', 'Area', 'Timezone', 'Job','Education','Employment','Services','VitD_levels'). Also, binomial "Yes"/"No" or "Male"/"Female", variables were encoded to 1/0,respectively and for other significant catgeorical variables dummies are generated. This resulted in 35 remaining numerical independent predictor variables, including the target variable(ReAdmis). The dataset appeares to be sufficiently cleaned leaving no null, NAs or missing data points.Measures of central tendency through histograms normal distributions for "VitD_levels" and "Age",bi-modal distribution for 'Initial_days',right skewed distribution for 'Full_meals_eaten' and 'Additional_charges'. The cleaned dataset no longer retained any outliers.The average patient is of 'Age' 53 with a std deviation of 18,average total charge per day is '5891' and the maximum 'Adiitional_charge' is '30566'..

C.3 • Import original dataset to Python. • Rename columns/variables of survey to easily recognizable column names (ex: "Item1" to "Timely_admission"). • Remove the extra 'Unamed' column name from the data set • Get a description of dataframe, structure (columns & rows) & data types. • View summary statistics. • Drop less meaningful identifying (ex: "CaseOrder") & demographic columns (ex: Lat,Lng) from dataframe. • Check for records with missing data & impute missing data with meaningful measures of central tendency (mean, median or mode) or simply remove outliers that are several standard deviations above the mean. • Create dummy variables in order to encode categorical, yes/no data points into 1/0 numerical values. • Check unique values for Marital,Initial_admin,Complication_risk and generate dummies for these variables using pandas package. • View univariate & bivariate visualizations. • Prepared dataset will be extracted & provided as "md_prepared.csv"

#Create dummy variables in order to encode categorical, yes/no data points into 1/0 numerical values.
md_df['D.Gender'] = [1 if v == 'Male' else 0 for v in md_df['Gender']]
md_df['D.ReAdmis'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['ReAdmis']]
md_df['D.Soft_drink'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['Soft_drink']]
md_df['D.HighBlood'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['HighBlood']]
md_df['D.Stroke'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['Stroke']]
md_df['D.Overweight'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['Overweight']]
md_df['D.Arthritis'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['Arthritis']]
md_df['D.Diabetes'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['Diabetes']]
md_df['D.Hyperlipidemia'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['Hyperlipidemia']]
md_df['D.BackPain'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['BackPain']]
md_df['D.Anxiety'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['Anxiety']]
md_df['D.Allergic_rhinitis'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['Allergic_rhinitis']]
md_df['D.Reflux_esophagitis'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['Reflux_esophagitis']]
md_df['D.Asthma'] = [1 if v == 'Yes' else 0 for v in md_df['Asthma']]

#Confusion Matrix and Accuracy score for initial model
y_data = md_df['D.ReAdmis']
x_data = md_df.drop('D.ReAdmis', axis = 1)
x_training_data, x_test_data, y_training_data, y_test_data = train_test_split(x_data, y_data, test_size = 0.25)
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(x_training_data, y_training_data)
predictions = model.predict(x_test_data)
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
print(classification_report(y_test_data, predictions))
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
CM=confusion_matrix(y_test_data,predictions)
print(CM)
axes = sns.heatmap(CM, annot=True,cmap='nipy_spectral_r', fmt='g')

Part V: Data Summary and Implications¶

F.1 The regression equation for the reduced model is y=9.840-0.0012Age+0.0111Initial_days+2.976e-05TotalCharge+3.52e-06Options-0.0088Options-0.0116Courteous_staff-0.0103Active_Listening-0.0277D.HighBlood-0.0189D.Allergic_rhinitis-0.0145D.Asthma

Each regression coefficient describes the estimated change in the log-odds of the response variable when the coefficient's predictor variable increases by one.

P-value for these are statistically and practically significant at 0.00. The limitation of the model is the size of data.

F.2 Course of action - It is important that the organization understand the inverse relationship between ReAdmis and other predictor variables.Example (options and Courteous_staff) working on these services for a patient by the hospital will help in reducing the 'ReAdmis' rate and improving the Initial days of the patient in the hospital will help in better treatment services.
